/**
 * \page installing_yac Configuration, Building and Installation for Different Systems

\tableofcontents

\section building_yac_req Requirements

  - MPI
  - LAPACK
    - If no external interface is provided (e.g. MKL, ATLAS, ...) the bundled
      (very limited) version of CLAPACK library is used.
  - <a href="https://github.com/pantoniou/libfyaml">libfyaml</a>
    - Only required for \ref yac_lib_mci.
  - <a href="https://gitlab.dkrz.de/dkrz-sw/yaxt">yaxt</a>
    (see \subpage installing_yaxt)
  - <a href="https://www.unidata.ucar.edu/software/netcdf/">NetCDF</a>
    - Not mandatory, but without it features like writing or
      reading weight files will be deactivated.
  - <a href="https://gitlab.dkrz.de/icon-libraries/libmtime">libmtime</a>
    - A bundled version is included in YAC, but an external one can be
      specified.
    - Only required for \ref yac_lib_mci.
  - Autoconf
    - Only required for configuration if you are not using a release (e.g., develop version).
  - Doxygen (recommended version 1.11.0, check `doxygen --version`)
    - Only required if you want to build the documentation via `doxygen doc/Doxyfile`
  - Graphviz
    - Only required if you want to build the documentation

\section getting_yac Getting YAC

Clone \ref availability "public repository of YAC".

\subsection getting_yac_whole Entire repository

Get the entire repository and optionally check out a specific release

\code
git clone https://gitlab.dkrz.de/dkrz-sw/yac.git
git -C yac checkout <release_tag>
\endcode

\subsection getting_yac_tag Specific Release

Alternatively get only the code for a specific release.

\code
git clone --depth 1 --branch <release_tag> https://gitlab.dkrz.de/dkrz-sw/yac.git
\endcode

\section building_yac Building YAC

After cloning the repositotory the folder `yac` contains all source code and
other files that belong to the software YAC.

For building YAC it is recommended to use a separate directory. The location is
arbitrary. To create the build directory inside the folder `yac` execute the
following commands:

\code
cd yac
mkdir build
\endcode

In the remainder of this section the folder `yac` will be referred to as
`<yac_repo_dir>` and the folder `<yac_repo_dir>/build` will be referred to as
`<yac_build_dir>`.

Unless explicitly specified when configuring the build directory, all
\ref yac_libs "YAC libraries", unit tests, examples, and
\ref yac_tools will be built.

\subsection building_yac_levante Building on HPC System at DKRZ (gcc 11.2.0, OpenMPI 4.1.2)

Information about the HPC-system Levante at DKRZ can be found
<a href="https://www.dkrz.de/en/systems/hpc/hlre-4-levante?set_language=en">here</a>.

Load toolchain

\code
module purge
module load \
        gcc/11.2.0-gcc-11.2.0 \
        openmpi/4.1.2-gcc-11.2.0 \
        netcdf-c/4.8.1-openmpi-4.1.2-gcc-11.2.0 \
        hdf5/1.12.1-openmpi-4.1.2-gcc-11.2.0 \
        intel-oneapi-mkl/2022.0.1-gcc-11.2.0
\endcode

YAC releases already contain a configure-script, if another YAC version
is used (e.g. master-branch), it has to be generated.

\code
cd <yac_repo_dir>
test -f ./configure || ./autogen.sh
\endcode

Configure build directory

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
<yac_repo_dir>/configure \
        CC=mpicc \
        FC=mpif90 \
        --disable-mpi-checks \
        --disable-silent-rules \
        --enable-concurrent-mpi-tests \
        --enable-python-bindings \
        --with-fyaml-root=/sw/spack-levante/libfyaml-0.7.12-fvbhgo \
        --with-netcdf-root=/sw/spack-levante/netcdf-c-4.8.1-6qheqr \
        --with-yaxt-root=<yaxt_inst_dir> \
        MKL_CFLAGS="`pkg-config --cflags mkl-static-lp64-seq`" \
        MKL_CLIBS="`pkg-config --libs mkl-static-lp64-seq`" \
        --prefix=<yac_inst_dir>
\endcode

Build

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make -j8
\endcode

Run tests

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make -j8 check
\endcode

Install

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make install
\endcode

\subsection building_yac_macOS Building on macOS 13.1 (Ventura) Apple M1 (homebrew gcc 12.2.0, OpenMPI 4.1.4, netcdf 4.9.0)

Generate configure-script in source directory (if required)

\code
cd <yac_repo_dir>
test -f ./configure || ./autogen.sh
\endcode

Configure build directory (with external libmtime and LAPACK)

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
<yac_repo_dir>/configure \
        --with-netcdf-root=/opt/homebrew \
        --with-fyaml-root=/opt/homebrew \
        --with-yaxt-root=<yaxt_inst_dir> \
        --disable-lib-only \
        --without-external-mtime \
        --enable-silent-rules \
        CC=/opt/homebrew/bin/mpicc \
        FC=/opt/homebrew/bin/mpif90 \
        CFLAGS="-g -Wall" \
        FCFLAGS="-g -Wall -fimplicit-none" \
        MPI_LAUNCH="$(which mpirun) --map-by socket:OVERSUBSCRIBE"
\endcode

Build

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make -j8
\endcode

Run tests

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make -j8 check
\endcode

Install

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make install
\endcode

\subsection building_yac_ubuntu Building on Ubuntu 24.04 (OpenMPI 4.1.6)

\warning
There is a bug with OpenMPI's MPMD on Ubuntu 25.04. Therefore, the use of
Ubuntu 25.04 is **not recommended** with YAC. Refer to
[github.com/open-mpi/ompi/issues/13303](https://github.com/open-mpi/ompi/issues/13303)
for further information.

First, install some basic dependencies via the package manager:

\code
apt install build-essential git libtool openmpi-bin libopenmpi-dev \
            libnetcdf-dev libfyaml-dev
\endcode

If you want to `--enable-python-bindings` (and test them) you also need:

\code
apt install libpython3-dev python3-setuptools python3-numpy python3-mpi4py \
            python3-netcdf4 python3-matplotlib python3-isodate cython3
\endcode

\note
`uxarray` does not offer installation via `apt`. This will lead to some tests
being skipped. If you still want to run these tests create a `venv` with the
option `--system-site-packages` and install `uxarray` using `pip`:
```sh
cd <yac_build_dir>
python3 -m venv --system-site-packages tests/python/.venv
source tests/python/.venv/bin/activate
pip install uxarray
```
Make sure to activate the venv before running the tests.

If you want to build the documentation you also need:

\code
apt install doxygen graphviz
\endcode

Please consider installing [Doxygen 11.1.0](https://github.com/doxygen/doxygen/releases/tag/Release_1_11_0)
if you experience issues in the documentation.

Generate configure-script in source directory

\code
cd <yac_repo_dir>
test -f ./configure || ./autogen.sh
\endcode

Configure build directory (with external libmtime and LAPACK)

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
<yac_repo_dir>/configure \
        CC=mpicc \
        FC=mpif90 \
        --enable-mpi-checks \
        --enable-silent-rules \
        --enable-concurrent-mpi-tests \
        --enable-python-bindings \
        --with-yaxt-root=<yaxt_inst_dir> \
        CFLAGS="-g -Wall" \
        FCFLAGS="-g -Wall -fimplicit-none" \
        MPI_LAUNCH="mpirun --oversubscribe" \
        --prefix=<yac_inst_dir>
\endcode

Build

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make -j8
\endcode

Run tests

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make -j8 check
\endcode

Install

\code
cd <yac_build_dir>
make install
\endcode

\note
Instead of setting `MPI_LAUNCH` during configuration above, you can configure your MPI to use the `--oversubscribe` option per default.
- OpenMPI 4 and earlier: Create the file `$HOME/.openmpi/mca-params.conf` and insert the following lines:
```
rmaps_base_oversubscribe=1
orte_create_session_dirs=1
```
- OpenMPI 5: Create the file `$HOME/.prte/mca-params.conf` and insert the line:
```
rmaps_default_mapping_policy = :oversubscribe
```

\subsubsection building_yac_legacy_ubuntu Building on Older Ubuntu Versions

\note
Information in this section may be outdated but still useful if you have to use
an older version of Ubuntu. Generally, it is recommended to use a recent OS
version.

It is also possible to build YAC on older Ubuntu versions by following the
instructions above. However, you might have to build some dependencies from
source. The following versions have been used to build YAC:

\paragraph building_yac_ubuntu_20_04 Ubuntu 20.04

You will have to build `libfyaml-dev` from source because it is not provided
in the package repositories:

1. Please clone [github.com/pantoniou/libfyaml](https://github.com/pantoniou/libfyaml) and
  follow the instructions for building and installation. It is recommended to
  install `libfyaml` into a user-specified directory `<libfyaml_inst_dir>`
  by using the `--prefix` option: `./configure --prefix=<libfyaml_inst_dir>`
2. The remaining steps are almost identical as for a recent Ubuntu. Please add the
  option `./configure ... --with-fyaml-root=<libfyaml_inst_dir> ...` when
  configuring the build process of YAC to make sure `libfyaml` can be found
  during the YAC build.

\section building_yac_examples Examples

By default together with the YAC library a couple of examples will be built.
They can be found in:

`<yac_build_dir>/examples/<example_name>`

Additional information on each example is available in:

`<yac_repo_dir>/examples/<example_name>/README`

\section linking_yac Linking with YAC

Using the
<a href="https://www.freedesktop.org/wiki/Software/pkg-config/">pkg-config</a>
tool, the variables for linking YAC to your program can be extracted.

Set search path for pkg-config

\code
export PKG_CONFIG_PATH=$PKG_CONFIG_PATH:<yac_inst_dir>/lib/pkgconfig
\endcode

Getting Parameters for C-Interface

\code
CC=`pkg-config --variable=cc yac-mci`
YAC_CFLAGS=`pkg-config --variable=cflags yac-mci`
YAC_CLIBS=`pkg-config --variable=clibs yac-mci`
\endcode

Getting Parameters for Fortran-Interface

\code
FC=`pkg-config --variable=fc yac-mci`
FCFLAGS=`pkg-config --variable=fcflags yac-mci`
FCLIBS=`pkg-config --variable=fclibs yac-mci`
\endcode
*/

/**
 * \page installing_yaxt Installing yaxt

\tableofcontents

Yet Another eXchange Tool (yaxt) is a communication library, which is a
requirement for building YAC.

Dokumentation: <a href="https://dkrz-sw.gitlab-pages.dkrz.de/yaxt/">https://dkrz-sw.gitlab-pages.dkrz.de/yaxt/</a>

Download: <a href="https://gitlab.dkrz.de/dkrz-sw/yaxt">https://gitlab.dkrz.de/dkrz-sw/yaxt</a>

\section building_yaxt_req Requirements

  - MPI

\section getting_yaxt Getting yaxt

Clone public repository of yaxt.

\subsection getting_yaxt_whole Entire Repository

Get the entire repository and optionally check out a specific release

\code
git clone https://gitlab.dkrz.de/dkrz-sw/yaxt.git
git -C yaxt checkout <release_tag>
\endcode

\subsection getting_yaxt_tag Specific Release

Alternatively get only the code for a specific release.

\code
git clone --depth 1 --branch <release_tag> https://gitlab.dkrz.de/dkrz-sw/yaxt.git
\endcode

\section building_yaxt Building yaxt

After cloning the repository the folder `yaxt` contains all source code and
other files that belong to the software yaxt.

For building yaxt it is recommended to use a separate directory. The location is
arbitrary. To create the build directory inside the folder `yaxt` execute the
following commands:

\code
cd yaxt
mkdir build
\endcode

In the remainder of this section the folder `yaxt` will be referred to as
`<yaxt_repo_dir>` and the folder `<yaxt_repo_dir>/build` will be referred to as
`<yaxt_build_dir>`.

\subsection building_yaxt_levante Building on HPC System at DKRZ (gcc 11.2.0, OpenMPI 4.1.2)

Information about the HPC-system Levante at DKRZ can be found
<a href="https://www.dkrz.de/en/systems/hpc/hlre-4-levante?set_language=en">here</a>.

Load toolchain

\code
module purge
module load \
        gcc/11.2.0-gcc-11.2.0 \
        openmpi/4.1.2-gcc-11.2.0
\endcode

Generate configure-script in source directory

\code
cd <yaxt_repo_dir>
./scripts/reconfigure
\endcode

Configure build directory

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
<yaxt_repo_dir>/configure \
        CC=mpicc \
        FC=mpif90 \
        --prefix=<yaxt_inst_dir>
\endcode

Build

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make -j8
\endcode

Run tests

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make -j8 check
\endcode

Install

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make install
\endcode

\subsection building_yaxt_macos Building on macOS 13.1 (Ventura) Apple M1 (homebrew gcc 12.2.0, OpenMPI 4.1.4, netcdf 4.9.0)

Generate configure-script in source directory

\code
cd <yaxt_repo_dir>
./scripts/reconfigure
\endcode

Configure build directory

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
<yaxt_repo_dir>/configure \
  MPI_LAUNCH="$(which mpirun) --map-by socket:OVERSUBSCRIBE" \
  --prefix=<yaxt_inst_dir> \
  --disable-shared
\endcode

Build

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make -j8
\endcode

Run tests

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make -j8 check
\endcode

Install

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make install
\endcode

\subsection building_yaxt_ubuntu Building on Ubuntu 24.04 / 25.04 (OpenMPI 4.1.6)

First, install some basic dependencies via the package manager:

\code
apt install build-essential git libtool openmpi-bin libopenmpi-dev
\endcode

Generate configure-script in source directory

\code
cd <yaxt_repo_dir>
./scripts/reconfigure
\endcode

Create a build directory and configure it

\code
mkdir <yaxt_build_dir>
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
<yaxt_repo_dir>/configure \
  CC=mpicc \
  FC=mpif90 \
  MPI_LAUNCH="mpirun --oversubscribe" \
  --prefix=<yaxt_inst_dir> \
\endcode

Build

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make -j8
\endcode

Run tests

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make -j8 check
\endcode

Install

\code
cd <yaxt_build_dir>
make install
\endcode

\note
Instead of setting `MPI_LAUNCH` during configuration above, you can configure your MPI to use the `--oversubscribe` option per default.
- OpenMPI 4 and earlier: Create the file `$HOME/.openmpi/mca-params.conf` and insert the following lines:
```
rmaps_base_oversubscribe=1
orte_create_session_dirs=1
```
- OpenMPI 5: Create the file `$HOME/.prte/mca-params.conf` and insert the line:
```
rmaps_default_mapping_policy = :oversubscribe
```
*/
